## Vercel Web Analytics Implementation

Successfully implemented Vercel Web Analytics for the Next.js Pages Router project.

### Changes Made

#### 1. Installed Package
- Added `@vercel/analytics` (v1.6.1) to dependencies
- Used npm as the package manager (matching project convention)

#### 2. Modified Files
- **src/pages/_app.tsx**:
  - Added import: `import { Analytics } from '@vercel/analytics/next';`
  - Added `<Analytics />` component inside the `<Provider>` wrapper, after the main content div
  - Placement ensures analytics tracking across all pages while respecting the existing component hierarchy

#### 3. Updated Dependencies
- **package.json**: Added @vercel/analytics dependency
- **package-lock.json**: Updated with new package and its dependencies

### Implementation Details

The Analytics component was placed strategically:
- Inside the Redux Provider to ensure it has access to the app state if needed
- After the main content div to avoid interfering with the app's layout
- Outside the conditional Navbar/Footer rendering to track all routes (including admin routes)

This placement ensures:
✓ Analytics loads on all pages (both user-facing and admin pages)
✓ No disruption to existing functionality
✓ Proper integration with the Redux store and authentication flow

### Verification

- ✅ TypeScript compilation successful
- ✅ Next.js build completed without errors
- ✅ No breaking changes to existing functionality
- ✅ Analytics component properly imported and rendered

### Project Type
This is a **Pages Router** Next.js project with TypeScript, using src/ directory structure.

The implementation follows Next.js best practices for Pages Router applications as documented in the Vercel Analytics documentation.
